<section xml:id="C18.S25">
<title>Wilson Class: Definitions</title>        
   
<subsection xml:id="C18.S25.SS1">
<title>Preliminaries</title>        
 
<para xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="1" xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p1.s1">
For the Wilson class OP’s <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p1.m1">p_{n}(x)</Math> with <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p1.m2">x=\lambda(y)</Math> : if the <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p1.m3">y</Math> -orthogonality set is <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p1.m4">\{0,1,\dots,N\}</Math> , then the role of the differentiation operator <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p1.m5">\ifrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}</Math> in the Jacobi, Laguerre, and Hermite cases is played by the operator <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p1.m6">\Delta_{y}</Math> followed by division by <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p1.m7">\Delta_{y}(\lambda(y))</Math> , or by the operator <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p1.m8">\nabla_{y}</Math> followed by division by <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p1.m9">\nabla_{y}(\lambda(y))</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="2" xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p1.s2">
Alternatively if the <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p1.m10">y</Math> -orthogonality interval is <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p1.m11">(0,\infty)</Math> , then the role of <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p1.m12">\ifrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}</Math> is played by the operator <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p1.m13">\delta_{y}</Math> followed by division by <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p1.m14">\delta_{y}(\lambda(y))</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>

 
<para xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="3" xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p2.s1">
Table 18.25.1 lists the transformations of variable, orthogonality ranges, and parameter constraints that are needed in §18.2(i) for the Wilson polynomials <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p2.m1">W_{n}\left(x;a,b,c,d\right)</Math> , continuous dual Hahn polynomials <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p2.m2">S_{n}\left(x;a,b,c\right)</Math> , Racah polynomials <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p2.m3">R_{n}\left(x;\alpha,\beta,\gamma,\delta\right)</Math> , and dual Hahn polynomials <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S25.SS1.p2.m4">R_{n}\left(x;\gamma,\delta,N\right)</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
        
  
